Comment: It is a good action-adventure movie, that uses a different narrative from the original story, showing us the main character already in the present and using flashbacks to tell us his dramatic past. It's a decent rereading from an old and classic story, now using all technologies and computer graphics that helps to make a beautiful photography and nice special effects scenes. Title: The Legend of Tarzan - Official Teaser Trailer [HD]
Comment: Big Tarzan fan here. I read the novel a few times, loved "Greystoke: The Legend of Tarzan" (the definitive Tarzan flick for me) and even dug the Johnny Weissmuller movies as a kid, but man, the new movie... meh.The new "The Legend of Tarzan" (not to be confused with the Greystoke movie) is just not that great. The True Blood guy is great in the roll of Tarzan. He's a good actor anyway. But Samuel L. Jackson in a Tarzan movie... really? Seems he can play ONE character and just doesn't seem to have the acting chops to not be the "Pulp Fiction guy" in every movie. When you have a movie that's taking place in the 1800s, it's kind of stupid for one of the characters to play it like it's the modern day. The movie had potential but his character just was completely unnecessary, unfunny, and distracting. It's like movie studios think "We need to have a guy to say funny things to keep people's attention. We need to give him a 'catch phrase'. Have him say 'Do you want me to kiss this gorilla's nuts?' people will love that!".  The movie's decent but don't believe the hype. It's not all that the marketing would have you believe. It's a rental. The cgi was kind of quirky as well. Too bad, I thought it was going to be way good. By the way, movie studios constantly wring their hands "Darnit, why aren't people going to the movies anymore??" $22 to get in (on a matinee) and $13 for a small soda and small popcorn (?!?!). Imagine taking a family to the movies- It'd be a month's pay. Yikes.

Before anyone is too harsh about "The Legend of Tarzan", on must remember that these Edgar Rice Burrows stories have been around for many decades and they still endure. Comment: Seriously, what's with the stupid human tribe in the jungle? Was that in the book or something? If so, that's one thing the Disney film did way better than the book. I thought the point was that Tarzan was in an extremely remote area of the world and didn't even know there were others of his species, let alone saw one. It made his identity crisis all the more compelling. Also, Christoph Waltz if probably my favourite actor, but they are going to keep his character German, right? Because there's no way anyone will believe he is an old British hunter. And any sense of gritty realism flew out the window when they put Samuel L Jackson in a room full of old, British, mutton chop-wearing white men in Victorian London who accept him as one of them. Okay. Most of my complaints are over. :)

Title: The Legend of Tarzan - Official Teaser Trailer [HD]
Comment: This looks like a TARZAN picture for those of us who came to know Tarzan from the Novels of EDGAR RICE BURROUGHS and not the Sol Lesser films. This film although not based on any of the novels is in keeping with how Tarzan was originally concieved by Burroughs---an English Lord raised by apes known to his peers in the House of Lords as John Clayton lll,Lord Greystoke.  Tarzan had that duality about him-----the feral wild child and the English Lord but no matter how civilized he conducted himself in so-called ""Civilized"" society he knew he didnt belong there. It was for the love of the beautiful blonde American woman JANE PORTER-CLAYTON that he retained his wealth and title of Lordship for her.But Jane knew when to bind him and when to let loose and he HAD to return to the Gabonese rain forest of West Africa revitalize himself. Please read: TARZAN ALIVE; The Biography of Lord Greystoke by PHILIP JOSE FARMER

All I can say is that this trailer was fantastic, it was visually beautiful, the landscape looked spectacular, definitely the cinematography will be the strongest part of this movie, because I've watched this trailer too many times just admiring the visuals of it, and also the actors, Margot Robbie looks beautiful as Jane Porter, always lovely to watch, Christoph Waltz as the villain, well I'm not sure about that, I'm sure that he is a great actor, but I'm not sure to see him as the villain, and Alexander Skarsgard as the titular character seems fine to me, although I'm pretty sure his fanclub will get more ladies after his portrayal, and Samuel L. Jackson, can't forget about Samuel L. Jackson seeing how he fits inside this cast, so good!   

But anyways, this movie is not related to the Disney animated movie, this character has existed for almost 100 years since Edgar Rice Burroughs wrote his first of twelve novels of the character which became popular and even before Disney made the animated movie, it will be based off stories from the original books, but not the Disney movie, as for David Yates as the director, I congratulate him, because seeing the fantastic job he did on Harry Potter makes me want to know more about his director skills, my favorite part was at the end when Tarzan was drinking the coffee, acting natural even though many of the men in the office knew who he was, and the cut!, the final cut of the trailer where Tarzan and the chief Ape get ready to fight, Legendary!!

Comment: Indeed I have to agree with some of you who commented that most people seem to know only the Disney movie. Anyone who read the original story would tell you that the Disney version of Tarzan (as a character) had very little to do with what's in the original book. The book depicts a very sad and essentially a very lonely existence that is filled with plenty of violence that he both received and handed out. Plain and simple, Tarzan in the book becomes a killer. He kills for survival, he kills for revenge and he kills for pleasure. I don't think that the things that are in the book would ever make it to the big screen but I would still watch it just to see how close did they dare to get to the original story.

Title: The Legend of Tarzan - Official Teaser Trailer [HD]
Comment: You can't compare this version to the Disney version because the Disney version was made for kids, and was different from the original story. Despite its dark moments, Disney's Tarzan was still a very upbeat movie. This seems to be going more gritty, more adult-oriented. So it shouldn't be a surprise that the musical aspect is gone. That would be like if Christian Bale played batman in the Dark Knight Rises, but still made jokes like those of Adam West's Batman from the 60s. That being said, I was somewhat confused by the casting choices for some of the roles. But since one of those roles is played by Christoph Waltz, an amazing actor who can fit possibly any role he's given, I get the feeling the casting choices will grow on me once I've seen more screen time from them.

Title: The Legend of Tarzan - Official Teaser Trailer [HD]
Comment: To everyone making references about "this better not ruin my childhood": Tarzan was a series of novels (well-written in my opinion) that were very gruesome at times. The story is remarkable but it was never meant to be a story for kids. Disney softened the Tarzan story by A LOT. This looks like it doesn't even want to follow the original story (which I'm ok with, movies are made for different perspectives most of the time). It looks like they just want to make an epic action adventure thing with the story of Tarzan and make it their own. The original story of Tarzan is pretty neat and I'm sorry that it won't be translated in this film. Instead it feels like the jungle meets the avengers, typical Hollywood over-the-top effects with a mediocre story. I'm open minded and I will go see this. Happy holidays to all

Title: The Legend of Tarzan - Official Teaser Trailer [HD]
Comment:
When will studios learn that technology hasn't reached a point where we can have CGI humans. It is so obvious when Tarzan looks like he made out of playdough. Even the animal CGI is bad. After a movie like Dawn of the Planet of the Apes, no movie has any excuse to make poor CGI animals.

Now, all that said, if the story is great, and well told, then really the terrible CGI doesn't matter, but this doesn't look like it offers anything new to the story of Tarzan. It's like how every Batman and Spiderman movie has to show their origin. We've seen this played out so many times. What is the catch here that makes any of this worthwhile?

Title: The Legend of Tarzan - Official Teaser Trailer [HD]
Comment: Hmmm.... Okay, so I gotta admit, this is the first time I've seen anything of Tarzan that may even be remotely good. Maybe. One concern I had was how the apes looked, the cgi for them doesn't look up to scratch, especially for a movie that's coming out in 2016. My only guess is is that the movie itself has not finished shooting and these bits were the only ones they touched up to release as a teaser, so hopefully there will be a lot more work put into making them look photorealistic, technically the cgi in this movie should look better than the planet of the apes movies. I'm also glad they didn't try to drag Tarzan into the future and have him live in New York or something as I've always hated that about Tarzan movies. I like Margot Robbie, but can't really see her as Jane, she seems miscast in my opinion. Hopefully this could be the Tarzan movie to stand alongside the Disney movie, perhaps even surpass it... Maybe? We'll have to wait and see.
